gtr:grantReference>PTA-026-27-1102</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>Focusing on the Scottish Conservatives, previous research was carried out on the impact of devolution on electioneering, statecraft, political activism, local knowledge and ?change? in rural Scotland. Ethnographic fieldwork was conducted in Dumfries and Galloway between the Foot and Mouth crisis of 2001 and the Scottish Parliament and local Council elections held on 1 May 2003. The following predicament ? with which both the anthropologist and would-be political activist are confronted ? is highlighted in this study: where does one go to locate relevant political action and knowledge?&lt;/p>

&lt;p>One of the unanswered questions of this research is whether the marginal status of the ethnographic subjects considered here is a condition of their geographical and/or institutional location or whether, in fact, their experiences of activism are shared by others situated closer to the political ?centre?? In addition to disseminating the results of this previous study through publications and conference papers, new research is proposed that will enable a comparative perspective with US politics to be developed. To assist with the drafting of a new research proposal, at least one preliminary research visit to Washington DC will be carried out.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2007-01-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2006-02-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>32146</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>05C30A17-BB45-431F-A62D-23478A7AC0EF</gtr:id><gtr:title>Devolution and the Scottish Conservatives - Banal Activism, Electioneering and the Politics of Irrelevance</gtr:title><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/b57ccfaab2cedb549155707885444d88"><gtr:id>b57ccfaab2cedb549155707885444d88</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Smith A</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2011-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:isbn>9780719079696</gtr:isbn><gtr:outcomeId>m_6239646911136037dc</gtr:outco